## 5. Testing Connectivity

Now that the peering connection, route tables, and security groups are configured, it's time to verify that instances in the peered VPCs can communicate.

**5-a.** Navigate to the **EC2 Dashboard** and note the **Private IPv4 address** of the instance in VPC-B.

![Step 5a - EC2 Instance Details](https://kimi-web-img.moonshot.cn/img/networkproguide.com/7cfe05f5e389d859197e980650ba51397140d114.png)

**5-b.** SSH into the EC2 instance in VPC-A using its public IP (or via Session Manager).

**5-c.** From the VPC-A instance, run a ping test to the private IP of the VPC-B instance:

```bash
ping <private-ip-of-vpc-b-instance>
```

**5-d.** If everything is configured correctly, you should see successful ping responses:

```
PING 10.1.1.187 (10.1.1.187) 56(84) bytes of data.
64 bytes from 10.1.1.187: icmp_seq=1 ttl=64 time=1.23 ms
64 bytes from 10.1.1.187: icmp_seq=2 ttl=64 time=0.98 ms
```

**5-e.** You can also test connectivity from VPC-B to VPC-A by SSH-ing into the VPC-B instance and pinging the private IP of the VPC-A instance.

> **Troubleshooting Tip:** If ping fails, double-check:
> 1. Route tables in both VPCs have correct routes to the peer VPC CIDR via the peering connection.
> 2. Security groups allow inbound ICMP from the peer VPC CIDR.
> 3. Network ACLs are not blocking the traffic.
> 4. The peering connection status is **Active**.

